    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but i'm still a bit confused about how the air actually stays stuck to the wing like that. why doesnt it just peel away from the top surface when the plane is moving really fast or hitting turbulence?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The principle that keeps the air clinging to the wing's surface is called the Coanda effect, working in concert with Bernoulli's principle. As air passes over the curved top surface of the wing and speeds up, it adheres to the contour of the wing due to surface tension and fluid dynamics. This cohesion between the air and the surface is strong when the pressure differential is created by the higher speed of moving air over the upper surface as described earlier. Even in high-speed conditions or turbulence, the sum of the forces acting on the airflow generally maintains adherence due to the pressure balance. The forward motion and design of the wing help maintain a smooth, attached flow of air over the surface, minimizing separation and ensuring consistent lift generation.",
