    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok so if the air is just following the shape of the wing, what happens when that flow breaks? like if the wing is at too steep an angle, does the air just suddenly stop following the curve and make the plane drop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When the airflow separates from the surface of the wing, known as flow reversal, it occurs due to a combination of factors, including the angle of attack being too steep and turbulent interactions. As a wing is angled upwards, if the angle becomes excessive, it eventually surpasses the critical angle of attack, at which point the smooth airflow that contributes to lift can no longer adhere to the surface. The upper layer of the air may then separate from the wing, causing a drop in lift, known as a stall. This separation occurs because the pressure on the top surface rapidly rises until the airflow cannot stay attached, even with the wing's curvature. Controlled levels of turbulence and safe angles of attack are maintained to ensure the wing remains adequately attached and stable, especially during maneuvering at the edges of its flight envelope. Pilot training and advanced design mitigate the risks of excessive angle of attack and potential stalls.",
